0":"1440","1380":"1380","1403":"1403","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1401":"1401","living 1427":"1427","about 1427":"about 1427","1453":"1453","1407":"1407","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Appleton, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Appleton, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","at Fifield, Oxford, England":"Fifield, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Baddesley Clinton, Worcestershire, England":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Caversfield, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Caversfield, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Denton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called. The vast majority, including those in Cambridgeshire, Cumbria, Dumfries, Durham, Kent, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Oxfordshire, Sussex, and Yorkshire are named from Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ (see   Dean   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. An isolated example in Northamptonshire appears in the Domesday Book as <i>Dodintone</i> meaning ‘enclosure, settlement associated with <i>Dodda</i> or <i>Dudda</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dean","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Denton was born in 1401, in Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Denton, was 21 and his mother, Jane Webb, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Baldington. He died in 1427, in Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1401–1427":"1401–1427","1407–1435":"1407–1435","1403–1428":"1403–1428","1427–1453":"1427–1453","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1385–1440":"1385–1440","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1380":"1380","1403":"1403","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1401":"1401","living 1427":"1427","about 1427":"umbes 1427","1453":"1453","1407":"1407","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Appleton, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Appleton, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","at Fifield, Oxford, England":"Fifield, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Baddesley Clinton, Worcestershire, England":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caversfield, Oxfordshire, En